{
  "doc_id": "42434",
  "text": "Although other studies have shown that marine invertebrate larvae can discriminate between particles based on size [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , to our knowledge our work is the first to show that echinoderm larvae can discriminate between food and non-food items as is common for other taxa [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . As some of the highest concentrations of microplastics are found in ocean gyres [CITATION_6] , ingestion of microplastics in these oligotrophic habitats may therefore be exacerbated by a lack of available food. Conversely, ingestion of microplastics in eutrophic coastal waters may be reduced because of the ability of larvae to discriminate between inert plastics and widely available food.",
